Circuit Breaker pattern prevents cascading failures in microservices by stopping calls to failing services and allowing them time to recover.

States:

```
CLOSED (Normal) ─→ [Threshold failures] ─→ OPEN (Failing)
    ↑                                         ↓
    └─────────── [Timeout] ←── HALF_OPEN ──┘
```

Implementation with Resilience4j:

```java
@Service
public class PaymentService {

    private final CircuitBreaker circuitBreaker;
    private final RestTemplate restTemplate;

    public PaymentService(RestTemplate restTemplate) {
        this.restTemplate = restTemplate;

        // Configure circuit breaker
        CircuitBreakerConfig config = CircuitBreakerConfig.custom()
            .failureThreshold(50)              // Fail after 50% errors
            .slowCallThreshold(50)             // Fail after 50% slow calls
            .waitDurationInOpenState(Duration.ofSeconds(30))
            .slowCallDurationThreshold(Duration.ofSeconds(2))
            .permittedNumberOfCallsInHalfOpenState(5)
            .build();

        this.circuitBreaker = CircuitBreaker.of("payment-service", config);
    }

    public void processPayment(String transactionId, Double amount) {
        Supplier<Void> supplier = () -> {
            try {
                callPaymentService(transactionId, amount);
                return null;
            } catch (Exception e) {
                throw new RuntimeException(e);
            }
        };

        // Execute with circuit breaker
        circuitBreaker.executeSupplier(supplier);
    }

    private void callPaymentService(String transactionId, Double amount) {
        restTemplate.postForObject(
            "http://payment-service/process",
            new PaymentRequest(transactionId, amount),
            String.class
        );
    }
}
```

